{{about|the song|the play|To Be Young, Gifted and Black (play)}} {{refimprove|date=March 2010}} {{Infobox song <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Songs --> | Name = To Be Young, Gifted and Black | Type = Song | Artist = [[Nina Simone]] | Album = [[Black Gold (Nina Simone album)|Black Gold]] | Released = 1970 | Recorded = October 26, 1969 | Venue = [[Avery Fisher Hall|Philharmonic Hall]], New York City | Genre = [[Soul music|Soul]], [[blues]], [[Gospel music|gospel]] | Length = 9:34 | Lyricist = [[Weldon Irvine]] | Composer = Nina Simone | Label = [[RCA Records|RCA]] | Producer = Stroud Productions }}
"'''To Be Young, Gifted and Black'''" is a song by [[Nina Simone]] with [[lyrics]] by [[Weldon Irvine]]. It was written in memory of Simone's late friend [[Lorraine Hansberry]], author of the play ''[[A Raisin in the Sun]]'', who had died in 1965 aged 34. The song was originally recorded and released by Simone in 1969, also featuring on her 1970 album ''[[Black Gold (Nina Simone album)|Black Gold]]'', and was a [[Civil Rights Movement]] anthem. Released as a [[Single (music)|single]], it peaked at number eight on the R&B chart and number 76 on the [[Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=528}}</ref>
Notable [[cover version]]s of the song were recorded by [[Donny Hathaway]] (on his 1970 album ''[[Everything Is Everything (Donny Hathaway album)|Everything Is Everything]]''), [[Aretha Franklin]] (on her 1972 album ''[[Young, Gifted and Black]]'') and [[Bob and Marcia]] (whose 1970 recording reached number 5 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number 15 in Ireland).<ref name="British Hit Singles & Albums">{{cite book | first= David | last= Roberts | year= 2006 | title= [[British Hit Singles & Albums]] | edition= 19th | publisher= Guinness World Records Limited | location= London | isbn= 1-904994-10-5 | page= 67}}</ref> Jamaican [[rocksteady]]/[[reggae]] trio The [[Heptones]] recorded a version for [[Coxsone Dodd]]'s [[Studio One (record label)|Studio One]] label in 1970. American singer [[Meshell Ndegeocello]] included a version on her 2012 tribute album ''[[Pour_une_Âme_Souveraine:_A_Dedication_to_Nina_Simone|Pour une Âme Souveraine: A Dedication to Nina Simone]]''.
[[Elton John]] recorded a version of "To Be Young, Gifted and Black" prior to his solo success. Intended to be released as a low-budget [[sound-alike]] version of the original, it was later reissued on the [[compilation album]] ''[[Chartbusters Go Pop! 20 Legendary Covers from 1969/70 as Sung by Elton John|Covers as Sung by Elton John]]''.
The song has also become a popular sample amongst various modern R&B/hip-hop pieces, including [[Rah Digga]]'s 2003 unreleased record "On the Move", [[Faith Evans]]' 2014 single "[[I Deserve It]]", featuring [[Missy Elliott]] and [[Sharaya J]], and on the title track of Rapsody's 2017 album ''Laila's Wisdom''.
